CEDAR CREEK WIND ENERGY, LLC MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
1. Availability: Cedar Creek Wind Energy, LLC ("Cedar Creek") makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Cedar Creek also makes available to any purchaser the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 1:
Third Party Provider
Third-party ancillary services: Cedar Creek offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all sales of electric energy, capacity, and/or ancillary services by Cedar Creek, which are (a) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission.
3. Rates: All sales pursuant to this Tariff shall be made at rates negotiated between the purchaser and Cedar Creek.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Cedar Creek.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Cedar Creek shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Cedar Creek's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Cedar Creek to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Cedar Creek's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Cedar Creek's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Cedar Creek has been granted the following waivers and exemptions in connection with its market-based rate authority: (i) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (ii) waiver of Part 41, Part 101, and Part 141 of the Commission's regulations, except for 18 C.F.R. 141.14 and 141.15; and (iii) blanket authorization under Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824c, and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities. See Letter Order, Cedar Creek Wind Energy, LLC, Docket Nos. ER07-1105-000, et al. (issued Aug. 8, 2007).
7. Seller Category: Cedar Creek is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northwest region, and a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Central, Northeast, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions. 8. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on such date as set by the Commission.

CERTIFICATE OF CONCURRENCE
This is to certify that Cedar Creek Wind Energy, LLC ("Cedar Creek") assents to and concurs with the Cotenancy, Common Facilities and Easement Agreement between Cedar Creek and Cedar Creek II, LLC ("Cedar Creek II"), dated December 16, 2010, which Cedar Creek II, the designated filing company, has filed in its "Rate Schedules and Tariffs" database.
Name of Tariff Adopted by Reference: Cotenancy, Common Facilities and Easement Agreement Between Cedar Creek Wind Energy, LLC and Cedar Creek II, LLC, dated December 16, 2010
DEI Tariff Record Adopted by Reference: Cotenancy Agreement, FERC Electric Rate Schedule No. 1
Description of Tariff: Cotenancy Agreement memorializing the terms and conditions under which Cedar Creek and Cedar Creek II own, utilize, operate, and maintain certain common facilities for the purpose of interconnecting their generating facilities with the transmission system owned and operated by the Public Service Company of Colorado. The Cotenancy Agreement does not establish rates, terms, or conditions for the provision of a FERC-jurisdictional service to any party.

Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Cedar Creek's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Cedar Creek to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Cedar Creek's market-based rate authority. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Cedar Creek has been granted the following waivers and exemptions in connection with its market-based rate authority: (i) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (ii) waiver of Part 41, Part 101 with the exception that waiver of the provisions that apply to hydropower licensees has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects, and Part 141 of the Commission's regulations, except for 18 C.F.R. 141.14 and 141.15; and (iii) blanket authorization under Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824c, and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities. Seller may not make sales of capacity, energy, and/or ancillary services at market-based rates within the balancing authority area of Puget Sound Energy, Inc. (PSE). See Puget Sound Energy, Inc., 181 FERC 61,008 (2022).
7. Mitigated Sales: Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between the Seller's mitigated balancing authority area (the PSE balancing authority area) and a balancing authority area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where the Seller has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if the Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. Seller must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above.
8. Seller Category: Cedar Creek is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northwest region, and a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Central, Northeast, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions. 9.
